question_text: Which sentence from the excerpt best supports the idea that there were different levels of education for a scribe?
options: “However, contrary to popular belief, not all Egyptian scribes understood hieroglyphs.” (paragraph 1)
“For everyday purposes, however, scribes used a shorthand version of the hieroglyphic script known as hieratic, which was quicker to write and more economical of space.” (paragraph 2)
“This limited the scope for employment but such ‘on the job’ training allowed apprentices to help out at home while learning.” (paragraph 4)
“For professions such as those of government official, priest or lawyer, a scribe would train for several more years, increasing his vocabulary to perhaps a thousand or more signs.” (paragraph 6)

question_text:
Read this sentence from paragraph 2.

 Including both ideograms (which convey a whole word or idea, either concrete or abstract, in a single sign) and phonograms (representing either an alphabetic sound or a group of consonants), [the writing system] was used in formal inscriptions on tomb and temple walls as well as on elaborate funerary papyri.

The author’s purpose for including the sentence is to
options: explain that hieroglyphs were reserved for royal and religious purposes.
demonstrate the methods experts use to interpret hieroglyphs.
clarify the significance of hieroglyphs in language and literature.
describe the basic features of hieroglyphs and how they were typically used.

question_text: Which statement summarizes the process that schools used to train scribes?
options: Boys had to memorize around 450 hieratic signs. Once they had learned these, they were expected to copy literary texts that contained valuable lessons.
Boys spent at least five years learning hieratic signs, which they practiced by copying texts. During this period, they were also introduced to basic hieroglyphs.
Boys spent five or six years learning the basics of hieratic script. After this period, they could become apprentices and begin learning hieroglyphics.
Boys were taught two different scripts. They practiced both types by copying lists and eventually progressed to writing letters, reports, and contracts.

question_text: Which claim is best supported by the information presented in paragraphs 3 and 4?
options: Education was difficult for the common citizens of Egypt to obtain.
Once students began studying to become scribes, their future held more possibilities.
If someone wanted to become a scribe, support from outside sources such as the government or a temple was necessary.
Becoming a successful scribe required a student’s family to sacrifice time and money in order to ensure the best education.

question_text: Hieratic script was particularly valuable in a bureaucratic government because
options: using hieratic script was an efficient way for scribes to produce large amounts of documentation.
many members of the general public could comprehend information that was written in hieratic script.
knowledge of hieratic script prepared scribes to serve their society in increasingly challenging roles.
people from different professional backgrounds could easily communicate with one another in hieratic script.

question_text: The diagram after paragraph 6 best provides additional support for the topic of the excerpt by
options: demonstrating the place of scribes in ancient Egyptian social structure.
depicting the types of tasks performed by each social class.
indicating that scribes were able to easily improve their social ranking.
comparing the social positions of each social class in ancient Egypt.

question_text: Based on the excerpt, which statement would the author most strongly agree with?
options: Boys in Egypt were encouraged to enter the same profession as older male relatives.
Knowledge of hieroglyphs was helpful to Egyptians who were interested in becoming scribes.
Hieratic script was more practical to ancient Egyptians than hieroglyphs were.
Boys in Egypt who studied for only a few years were unlikely to find employment as scribes

question_text:
Read these sentences from paragraph 2.

 Dad always said Mom could make all the dishes he’d had back in Vermont as well as though she were a New Englander herself, instead of a Russian. All of a sudden, I realized that tomorrow when those beans would be ready to eat I’d be going away. It gave me a funny feeling.

The sentences help develop a theme of the excerpt by
options: suggesting that life presents people with many challenges.
implying that the stress of major life events can cause confusion.
demonstrating that moving on from the familiar is a common human experience.
emphasizing the idea that people can easily learn the routines of being part of a new culture.

question_text:
Read this sentence from paragraph 3.

“I’ll be taking the train tomorrow night,” I said aloud, more to hear it myself.

This remark contributes to the conflict in the excerpt by
options: revealing Dad’s reasons for wanting to drive to the city.
causing tension between Mom and Dad.
leading Ellen to distance herself from both Mom and Dad.
showing Mom’s reluctance to plan that far in advance.

question_text:
Read this sentence from paragraph 9.

I tried to, and then I just sat still and looked straight at it.

How does the phrase “looked straight at it” contribute to the meaning of the excerpt?
options: It shows that Ellen is willing to deal with a problem directly instead of ignoring it
It suggests that Ellen studies all parts of an issue and not just its surface.
It illustrates that Ellen examines both sides of an argument.
It implies that Ellen is eager to seek wisdom from past experiences.

question_text: The words “cold” and “dark” affect the tone in paragraph 10 by
options: highlighting the feeling of unpredictability among the family members.
showing the feelings of anger and resentment Ellen directs toward her parents.
exaggerating the feeling of regret Dad experiences when leaving his family.
emphasizing the feelings of separation and loss that Ellen feels.

question_text: Which sentence from the excerpt provides evidence that Ellen has a lot in common with her father?
options: “He’s the one who gets excited when I do about spring coming or a serial running in the magazine we’re both reading. . . .” (paragraph 1)
“ ‘We can drive you into town in the afternoon,’ Dad said, dropping his paper on the floor.” (paragraph 4)
“ ‘Well, we don’t have to decide tonight,’ Dad said, but I knew he wanted to go into Clark City.” (paragraph 6)
“I wondered how they would get along without me.” (paragraph 25)

question_text:
Read these sentences from the excerpt.

 Mom seems to think of nothing farther away than today or perhaps yesterday or tomorrow morning. (paragraph 1)

Mom was fixing oatmeal for tomorrow morning. (paragraph 19)

The sentences help develop a central idea of the excerpt by
options: suggesting that practical people focus on current needs rather than worrying about the future.
showing that parents tend to consider the needs of their children before thinking of themselves.
revealing that it is sometimes important to plan ahead.
illustrating that dreaming about the future is a waste of time.

question_text: The flashback in paragraphs 10– 24 affects the plot by
options: showing that the departure of one member of the family makes extra work for those left on the farm.
showing that the bond within the family persists even when its members are apart.
explaining why Ellen fears that leaving her parents will be too difficult.
illustrating the close connection Ellen has with both of her parents.

question_text: Which sentence from the excerpt provides evidence that Mom wants Ellen to understand the family’s heritage?
options: “Mom folded the ironing board and put it inside their bedroom that was just off the kitchen.” (paragraph 2)
“ ‘There’s no need to go to town; she can catch the train at Gotham just as well.’ ” (paragraph 5)
“We’d go in right after dinner and go around to the stores, Dad going one way and Mom and I another.” (paragraph 7)
“ ‘Why, Yeléna, you know that; Anna Petrovna.’ ” (paragraph 22)

question_text:
Read this sentence from paragraph 2.

Two alumnae of its culinary program . . . were even recognized as semi- finalists for prestigious James Beard awards.

The words “recognized” and “prestigious” in the sentence convey that La Cocina
options: makes an effort to identify chefs who have a strong entrepreneurial work ethic.
has the ability to mentor chefs to reach the highest levels of achievement in their craft.
is focused on establishing local food entrepreneurs as celebrated professionals in their industry.
is dedicated to assisting chefs in developing new and innovative products.

question_text: Paragraph 4 contributes to the development of ideas about La Cocina in paragraph 1 by
options: specifying how La Cocina helps local food entrepreneurs become successful.
explaining what kind of goals La Cocina tries to set for local food entrepreneurs.
providing background information about local food entrepreneurs in San Francisco.
describing how Caleb Zigas discovered the need to provide assistance to local food entrepreneurs.

question_text: The quotation from Caleb Zigas in paragraph 6 conveys a central idea of the excerpt by
options: showing appreciation for the vibrant diversity of La Cocina.
communicating La Cocina’s goal of helping people of varying abilities.
describing a typical scenario at La Cocina.
emphasizing La Cocina’s focus on creating products.

question_text: The description of Mariko Grady’s background in paragraph 9 contributes to a central idea in the excerpt by
options: demonstrating what people are looking for when they come to La Cocina.
explaining why La Cocina is the best option for people starting out in the food business
showing how La Cocina can help people find success in the food business even though they have a background in something different.
confirming that La Cocina was originally established for small business owners who are looking to expand their services.

question_text: Which statement would the author most likely agree with?
options: The publicity efforts La Cocina engages in will help its business design spread to other cities.
The variety of exciting food available in San Francisco is due to the work of La Cocina.
La Cocina offers a method that will guarantee business ownership for qualified entrepreneurs.
La Cocina does admirable work in supporting the efforts of ambitious cooks who may have few resources.

question_text: Which piece of evidence from the excerpt is most relevant to the author’s claim that La Cocina provides an opportunity to become more established as a business owner?
options: the description of how two alumni of the business incubator have won food awards
the reference to a storytelling project where chefs relate their own backgrounds and business experiences
the lists of necessities such as business plans and city permits that La Cocina assists with
the notations of the criteria that applicants must meet to be endorsed by La Cocina in order to develop a small business

question_text: Which detail would be most important to include in a summary of the excerpt?
options: La Cocina produced a cookbook that includes some members’ stories.
La Cocina provides legal and technical assistance to its members.
Potential vendors need a market for their food before considering La Cocina.
There are different types of venues that food vendors from La Cocina use.

question_text: The table provides additional support for a central idea of the excerpt by
options: showing how La Cocina works with partner organizations to further educate and advance successful applicants within the food industry.
explaining how applicants are prepared to develop their own businesses once they leave La Cocina.
establishing that La Cocina is dedicated to its mission to provide delicious food to different communities.
emphasizing that applicants must be willing to dedicate time to promoting and developing their business with La Cocina.

question_text: The details in paragraph 1 contribute to a central idea of the passage by showing that Darimont
options: believed the Great Bear Rainforest was an ideal location to study wolves in their natural habitat because it is a protected area.
values different perspectives, because the information that Starr provided influenced the focus of Darimont’s research.
thought the Great Bear Rainforest would provide opportunities to study different groups of wolves because the area includes forests and islands.
understands the importance of respecting local community members, because Darimont sought permission from an elder of the Heiltsuk Nation before starting his research.

question_text: Why does the author include details about the conversation between Starr and Darimont in paragraph 2?
options: to explain why Starr had closely observed the relationship between the two groups of wolves Darimont wanted to study
to show that Darimont was hoping to work with Starr and to study both groups of wolves in the area
to highlight that Darimont was unfamiliar with the area and expected Starr to help him find wolves to study
to emphasize that the question asked by Starr caused Darimont to review his initial assumption about the wolves

question_text:
Read this sentence from paragraph 4.

After collecting and analyzing the DNA in 800 samples of gray fur and wolf waste, researchers could produce hard biological evidence that sea wolves had genetic markers that made them distinct from the mainland wolves.

The phrase “hard biological evidence” conveys that the goal of the research team was to
options: develop a procedure in order to ensure their study yielded plentiful data about the wolves.
seek definitive scientific proof of the number of wolf species present in the area of the study.
conduct a study to evaluate multiple theories about the diets of different wolf species.
discover if the new data would provide information different from that of previous studies.

question_text: The author uses the word “admits” in paragraph 5 most likely to
options: note that Darimont’s genetic research verified a theory based solely on field observations.
imply that Darimont’s study was disappointing because the conclusion that he reached was not original.
emphasize that Darimont’s study ultimately confirmed an idea that he had initially doubted.
highlight that Darimont’s results led him to draw a conclusion from his research that his team did not agree with

question_text: Which sentence from the passage best supports the idea that sea wolves had successfully adapted to living on the islands?
options: “While mainland wolves almost exclusively eat meat, such as deer and elk, and teach their young to hunt for land animals, sea wolves get as much as 90 percent of their nutrition from the sea and teach their young to dig for clams and to catch fish.” (paragraph 3)
“Sea wolves regularly swim between islands and have been known to sneak up on a seal sunning itself on a rock and make a leaping attack from the water.” (paragraph 3)
“Darimont suspects that some sea wolves live their entire life on the islands.” (paragraph 3)
“Darimont hypothesizes that a change in habitat led to the eventual genetic differences between sea wolves and mainland wolves.” (paragraph 4)

question_text: How did a change in habitat most affect the wolf population of the Great Bear Rainforest over time?
options: It caused some of the wolves to learn new hunting techniques in order to catch increasingly scarce prey.
It caused the wolves to form smaller packs and eventually separate, establishing distinct territories.
It caused some of the wolves to gradually become a new, genetically distinct species as they adapted behaviorally.
It caused the wolves to adapt their diet as different food sources became available in the area.

question_text:
Read lines 6– 7 from the poem.

The birds took their hops and zigzags a little more
 anxious; a home is a home; worms are worms.

What idea from the second stanza do the lines help develop?
options: The birds are eager for the return of warmer months.
The birds are most likely to thrive during the spring.
The birds naturally adjust to the seasonal changes.
The birds instinctively prepare for the future.

question_text:
Read lines 12– 14 from the poem.

And it was the leaves with a strong soft wind over them
 that talked most of all and said more than any others
 though speaking the fewest words.

What does the phrase “talked most of all” in line 13 convey?
options: It establishes that the speaker thinks the sound of wind in the leaves is the best indication that the season is changing.
It introduces the idea that the sound of the wind in the leaves remains constant throughout the seasons.
It suggests that the speaker is overwhelmed by the sounds of nature that emerge as the season changes.
It emphasizes that the sounds of nature enable the speaker to appreciate each season of the year.

question_text: How does the repetition of “ ‘This is the beginning of summer’ ” in lines 2– 3 and lines 18– 19 contribute to the meaning of the poem?
options: It suggests that the shift to summer occurs in the same way each year.
It emphasizes the idea that living things are prepared for the change of season.
It highlights the idea that the first signs of summer are surprising each year.
It builds expectations about what the natural world looks like during a change of season

question_text: Which lines from the poem best contrast with the idea of winter’s scarcity and bleakness?
options: The shrilling of the frogs was not so shrill as in the / first weeks after the broken winter;”(lines 4– 5)
“The yellow spreads of the dandelions and buttercups / reached across the green pastures.” (lines 8– 9)
“Tee whee and tee whee came on the breezes, and the grackles / chuzzled their syllables.” (lines 10– 11)
“Or if instead of counting up last year as against / this year, they count up this year as against next” (lines 25– 26)

question_text: How do lines 23– 28 contribute to a central idea of the poem?
options: They suggest that the speaker is aware of what has been lost in the winter
They imply that the birds sing the most in the summer.
They reveal that the birds are subject to the cycles of nature.
They emphasize that the speaker enjoys observing nature.

question_text: Throughout the poem, the poet conveys the speaker’s point of view by
options: gradually moving the speaker’s attention from one element of nature to another.
providing the speaker’s motivation for describing the landscape in great detail.
highlighting the speaker’s emotional response as each season passes.
shifting the speaker’s focus from external observations to personal reflection

question_text: Over the course of the poem, a central idea is developed mainly through the speaker’s
options: sense of eager anticipation as winter ends.
description of the changes in nature as the seasons transition.
observation of the birds’ behavior as summer begins.
prediction of future alterations in the physical landscape.

question_text: Which sentence from the excerpt supports the conclusion that Elton’s “militaristic ‘invasion’ metaphor” (paragraph 1) has influenced scientific understanding of non- native species?
options: “Among [Olden’s] findings: a substantial number of them said they would immediately eradicate a hypothetical non- native forest plant, even if it were shown to have no effect on the forest.” (paragraph 5)

“Regardless of what we label them, conservationists will be reluctant to remove them from their new environs— to do so would stymie their chances of adapting to the warmer future we’re creating.” (paragraph 8)
“A project to rip out and poison the spartina— which grows in dense swaths that exclude many other shorebirds— saw clapper rail numbers go tumbling downward.” (paragraph 10)
“In some cases we can best serve biodiversity by leaving the non- natives alone or even— brace yourself, now— introducing them on purpose.” (paragraph 14)

question_text: Climate change has affected efforts to manage invasive species mainly by causing ecologists to
options: call upon the public to be more tolerant of the presence of non- native species
admit that past attempts to eliminate non- native species have damaged the environment.
find ways of ensuring that native species are not harmed by the arrival of new species.
acknowledge that it is not realistic for some species to remain in their native habitats.

question_text: Which detail provides the most relevant support for the claim that “climate change is making it harder even to decide who the invaders are” (paragraph 7)?
options: the mention in paragraph 8 of non- native species that are forced to seek new habitats
the acknowledgment in paragraph 9 that non- native species include many domestic crops
the description in paragraph 11 of the interactions between native and non- native species
the account in paragraph 13 of an ecologist who changed his beliefs about nonnative species

question_text: The author’s use of cause and effect in paragraphs 10– 11 mainly emphasizes the idea that
options: some non- native species have helped their environments while others have had harmful impacts.
attempts to remove non- native species have seldom produced desired results.
some endangered native species have flourished because of the presence of nonnative species.
interactions between endangered native species and non- native species must be carefully monitored.

question_text: Which sentence from the excerpt supports the idea that some species are able to adjust to change?
options: “Native gardens have become increasingly popular, both as ways to celebrate the unique flora of each region and as tiny hot spots of diversity.” (paragraph 3)
“Many native (and beautiful) Hawaiian flowers are now pollinated by the Japanese white- eye bird— because the native pollinators have been driven extinct by other non- native species.”(paragraph 11)
“After all, nativeness is just one environmental value, and arguably not as important as preventing extinctions and preserving biodiversity.” (paragraph 14)
“The islands lost their own large tortoises, and the fruiting plants that formerly had their seeds moved around by these fruit- loving reptiles have been on the decline.” (paragraph 15)

question_text: The details in the section “A Good Thing, Not the Only Thing” convey a central idea of the excerpt by suggesting that
options: some non- native species can replace native species that are unable to survive on their own.
decisions about whether to keep non- native species should be considered on an individual basis.
the scientists who study rapidly changing ecosystems agree that non- native species enhance biodiversity.
a natural habitat that is healthy should be able to support a blend of native and nonnative species.

question_text: How does the chart provide additional support for a central idea of the excerpt?
options: by implying that the public becomes aware of non- native species only after removal is impossible
by showing that the complete removal of non- native species is usually not achievable after a certain period of time
by demonstrating why non- native species can be destructive if they are not removed from an area immediately
by explaining how some conservation groups have approached the removal of nonnative species

question_text: Which sentence should replace sentence 4 to more clearly introduce the topic of this passage?
options: Bike share programs have become an accessible and environmentally friendly solution for many urban travelers.
Bike share programs are successful because both residents and tourists can use the bicycles to travel within a city.
Bike share programs offer an alternative form of transportation in urban areas that is faster than using a car or taxi.
Bike share programs have created an affordable mode of transportation for people in large cities throughout the world.
